Dear Tyler: each time you appeared on shows promoting #fallfromgrace you attempted to justify why you are the sole writer for all of your series. Not one person chimed in, they just remained silent. Tyler, when people die and don't leave a will, they leave chaos and despair. If you don't delegate writing to the many talented, but underemployed, writers you're failing your legacy. Because if you die, every show dies. Every chance for your crew members to sustain their livelihoods dies. No rent. No mortgage. No college funds. Hiring writers is fulfilling a legacy that you've worked hard to build, but it's a legacy that should be able to continue with or without you. There are numerous black writers who gave up corporate careers to train in their craft. To be accepted to great writing programs you can't submit spec scripts of black shows. You have to submit Seinfelds, Friends, etc. But even then, upon completion, most of the writers who get hired are white and the black writers are waiting....for an opportunity, waiting before signing a 1-year lease on apartments and not even considering buying a home or starting a family. Tyler, hiring writers is more than keeping YOUR voice in the room, it's having the authority to change the trajectory of this often-jaded industry. And if you are called to Heaven, the show can go on because you have a succession plan in place so black talent can thrive, not merely fight to survive. What good is a Soundstage named after a legend if you silence the voices of writers who have dreams of excellence in the industry while hoping to have families like you have.  Please pray about it and I pray you consider flipping your script so other writers' dreams don't fade to black. @tylerperry
